pull_request.body:
Thanks for asking me to work on this. I will get started on it and keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original description:

> # KOALA Gaming Optimizer v2.3 - Critical Fixes and Rebranding
> 
> ## üéØ Primary Issues to Fix
> 
> ### 1. Program Rebranding
> - **Rename** the entire program to "KOALA Gaming Optimizer v2.3"
> - Update all references in the script, launcher, and documentation
> - Ensure version consistency across all files
> 
> ### 2. Critical PowerShell Syntax Error
> **Current Error:**
> ```
> [Error] Failed to detect GPU vendor: Die Benennung "if" wurde nicht als Name eines Cmdlet, einer Funktion, einer Skriptdatei oder eines ausf√ºhrbaren Programms erkannt.
> ```
> 
> **Root Cause:** The script uses PowerShell 7.0+ syntax (`??` null-coalescing operator) that doesn't work on PowerShell 5.1 (default on Windows 10/11).
> 
> **Fix Required:**
> - Replace ALL instances of `??` operator with PowerShell 5.1 compatible syntax
> - Use proper `if ($null -eq $variable)` checks instead
> - Ensure GPU vendor detection works on all PowerShell versions
> 
> ### 3. Dual GPU Detection Issue
> - Fix GPU detection logic to properly handle systems with multiple GPUs
> - Improve error handling for GPU vendor detection
> - Ensure compatibility with integrated + discrete GPU setups
> 
> ## üîß Technical Requirements
> 
> ### PowerShell Compatibility
> ```powershell
> # WRONG (PowerShell 7.0+ only):
> $vendor = $gpuVendor ?? "Unknown"
> 
> # CORRECT (PowerShell 5.1+ compatible):
> $vendor = if ($null -eq $gpuVendor) { "Unknown" } else { $gpuVendor }
> ```
> 
> ### GPU Detection Enhancement
> - Handle multiple GPU scenarios gracefully
> - Provide clear feedback when GPU detection fails
> - Fall back to generic optimization when GPU-specific detection fails
> 
> ### Version Updates
> - Update script header with v2.3
> - Update launcher bat file references
> - Update any hardcoded version strings
> - Ensure consistent branding throughout
> 
> ## üéÆ Expected Outcome
> 
> After this fix:
> - ‚úÖ Works on ALL Windows systems (PowerShell 5.1 and 7.0+)
> - ‚úÖ Proper GPU vendor detection without syntax errors
> - ‚úÖ Handles dual GPU systems correctly
> - ‚úÖ Consistent "KOALA Gaming Optimizer v2.3" branding
> - ‚úÖ No more German error messages about unrecognized cmdlets
> 
> ## üöÄ Priority: CRITICAL
> This is blocking users from running the optimizer on standard Windows installations.
> 
> ## üìã Files to Modify
> - `koalaoptimizerps1.ps1` - Main script with syntax fixes and rebranding
> - `KOALA_Launcher.bat` - Update version references
> - `README.md` - Update with v2.3 branding and compatibility info

feat(agents): Enhance red team agents with advanced strategies

This commit significantly upgrades the core red teaming agents by refining their system messages to enable more sophisticated attack and analysis strategies. The changes focus on shifting from simple keyword-based logic to advanced, vulnerability-driven methodologies.

- **Vulnerability-Driven Evaluation**: The `EvaluatorAgent` is re-engineered to perform a detailed diagnostic analysis instead of a simple pass/fail check. Its system message now defines specific vulnerability categories like **Chain-of-Thought Manipulation** and **Reward Hacking**, and its output is a structured JSON report. This provides a richer and more actionable feedback loop.
- **Strategic Introspection**: The `IntrospectionAgent` is renamed and its system message is overhauled to transform it into a **Red-Team Operations Strategist**. It is now responsible for analyzing the detailed evaluation report and providing strategic, high-level commands for the next attack, rather than simple pass/fail feedback.
- **Advanced Prompt Generation**: The `PromptGenerator`'s system message is expanded to include detailed examples for generating prompts for various vulnerability types. This empowers the agent to craft more sophisticated and targeted attacks.
- **Improved Conversation Flow**: A custom hook is added to the `GourmetAgent` to filter its chat history, ensuring it only receives messages from the user and the `PromptGenerator`. This prevents the target agent from being confused by internal agent communications (e.g., from the Evaluator or Introspection agents).
- **Simplified Speaker Selection**: The `speaker_selection_func` is simplified to match any agent name within the `PlannerAgent`'s message, making the flow logic more flexible.

docs: Add comprehensive README.md

This commit adds a detailed `README.md` file to the project. The new document provides a comprehensive guide for users on how to set up, configure, and run the `twinrad` multi-agent system.

- **Installation Instructions**: Includes step-by-step instructions for cloning the repository, setting up a virtual environment, and installing dependencies.
- **Configuration Guide**: Explains how to create a `.env` file and configure the necessary LLM API keys.
- **Usage Guide**: Provides clear commands for executing the main script and starting the red-teaming process.
- **System Overview**: Describes the roles and interactions of the different agents within the `GroupChat` workflow, giving users a clear understanding of the system's architecture and operation.

pull_request.body:
### Key Changes

This PR significantly enhances the `twinrad` red teaming framework by introducing more advanced, vulnerability-focused strategies and providing comprehensive user documentation.

* **Vulnerability-Driven Attacks**: Agents are now designed to analyze and exploit specific types of LLM vulnerabilities, such as **Chain-of-Thought Manipulation** and **Reward Hacking**.
* **Enhanced Agent Intelligence**: The `EvaluatorAgent` and `IntrospectionAgent` are upgraded to provide detailed, structured feedback, enabling a more sophisticated and strategic attack loop.
* **Improved User Experience**: A new, detailed **`README.md`** is added to guide users through the installation, configuration, and execution of the system, making it much easier to get started.

---

### Detailed Breakdown

These changes lay the groundwork for a more powerful and user-friendly red team platform.

* **Smarter Evaluation**: The `EvaluatorAgent`'s new JSON output format provides rich diagnostic information, which is a major improvement over the previous simple verdict. This allows the system to learn from its attacks in a more granular way.
* **Strategic Learning**: The `IntrospectionAgent` is refactored to act as a **Red-Team Operations Strategist**. It now takes the detailed evaluation report and generates a strategic recommendation, guiding the next attack with purpose.
* **Refined Communication**: A custom hook on the `GourmetAgent` ensures it only sees relevant messages, preventing it from being confused by internal agent-to-agent chatter. This isolates the target model and keeps the conversation focused.

---

### Technical Decisions

The decision to shift from simple, hardcoded rules to a vulnerability-driven approach was made to create a more robust and intelligent red team framework. By leveraging the LLMs themselves to understand and exploit nuanced vulnerabilities, we can achieve more sophisticated results. This also makes the system more modular and easier to extend with new vulnerability types in the future.

---

This PR is ready for review and represents a major leap forward for the `twinrad` project.

pull_request.title: [Core] Shared memory based object store for Multimodal data caching and IPC
pull_request.body:
## Essential Elements of an Effective PR Description Checklist
- [ ] The purpose of the PR, such as "Fix some issue (link existing issues this PR will resolve)".
- [ ] The test plan, such as providing test command.
- [ ] The test results, such as pasting the results comparison before and after, or e2e results
- [ ] (Optional) The necessary documentation update, such as updating `supported_models.md` and `examples` for a new model.


## Purpose
For improving multimodal data IPC and caching, CLOSE https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm/issues/19702

Major changes
1. Shared Memory Ring Buffer
Introduced a shared memory‚Äìbased ring buffer supporting `allocate` and `access` operations, designed for single-writer (broadcast) scenarios.
2. Object Store on Ring Buffer
Built an object store on top of the shared memory ring buffer, supporting `put` and `get` operations.

3. Improved IPC for TP > 1
MultiModalKwargs is now written to the object store before broadcasting in the engine process and retrieved by worker processes, improving IPC efficiency:
3.1. Reduces socket usage in MQ [overflow cases](https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm/blob/47db8c2c15209ca03dc57422d98518ca0199e657/vllm/distributed/device_communicators/shm_broadcast.py#L491) by offloading mm data to the object store. 
3.2 Replaces pickle with `MsgpackDecoder(MultiModalKwargs)` to reduce serialization overhead and memory copies.

4. Shared Memory Object Store as MM Cache
Added an option to use the shared memory object store instead of the LRU cache to improve multimodal cache performance:
4.1 In TP > 1 setups, `MultiModalKwargs` is written once by p0 and read directly by worker processes, avoiding redundant transmission through the engine process.
4.2 IPC for `MultiModalKwargs` between p0 and the engine process now uses shared memory instead of sockets.
4.3 Reduces memory footprint by avoiding duplicate storage of MultiModalKwargs in p0 and the engine process.


5. Trade-offs
5.1 The object store is not a full replacement for MQ, as it requires the reader to know the address provided by the writer, so we still need MQ to broadcast the address.
5.2 The current ring buffer is FIFO-based, which may not be ideal compared to LRU in certain scenarios.
